a plant, an animal, or a different human being. The thesis of the study is that the fantasy of metamorphosis challenges the narrator and his audience to confront certain basic anxieties about the human condition: Is the mind reducible to physical properties? What constitutes personhood? How does physical form affect personal identity and continuity of the self? Testing instances in which these and related perplexities appear in literature, Skulsky systematically and provocatively interprets ten major illustrative texts drawn from diverse epochs and languages, including the works of Homer, Ovid, Apuleius, Marie de France, Dante, Donne, Spenser, Keats, Kafka, and Woolf. Through Skulsky's masterly analysis the victims of metamorphosis in narrative literature--whether werewolf, ass, beetle, swine, or tree--provide a profound insight into the complexities of human experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aCreativiteit. 0aCréation littéraire. 0aCréation littéraire. 0aDeutsch. 0aEmpiricism. 0aEnglisch. 0aEnlightenment. 0aImagination. 0aLiteratur. 0aPhilosophie. 0aRomanticism. 0aRomantiek. 0aRomantik. 0aTheorie. 0aVerbeelding. 0aVerbeeldingskracht. 0aVerlichting (cultuurgeschiedenis). 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aMetamorphosis in literature. 4aPHILOSOPHY / General. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: World History eBook Packagez9783110353563oZDB-23-HWH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067442497540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067442498240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978067442498